message: The previous player's advice on grouping similar items and not combining more than two before using a tool is crucial. To reach 100 points, identify two soft ingredients (like paper, thread, mushroom, or feather), combine them, then use scissors on the resulting item, and finally use the frame tool on that cut item. For example, 'paper + mushroom' -> 'paper mushroom mix' -> 'cut paper mushroom mix' -> 'framed cut paper mushroom mix' = 100. Combining hard, natural items (like shell, wood, rock, pinecone) and then framing them will typically yield 20-25 points. Avoid combining an already framed item with another ingredient, as this can result in very low or negative values.

message: Scissors work best on soft items. Combining natural soft with artificial soft (e.g., mushroom + newspaper) then cutting gives the highest score (80). Combining two purely soft items (e.g., paper + yarn) then cutting gives 50. Avoid cutting hard items, even if mixed with soft, as it can lead to negative value. The Frame tool works best on hard items. Combining natural hard with artificial hard (e.g., rock + buttons) then framing gives 50. Purely hard natural items (e.g., pinecone + wood) or mixed natural hard/soft (e.g., shell + mushroom) when framed give 20. Prioritize the high-value soft mix for scissors, then the hard mix for frame.

message: The previous player's hints about grouping soft items for scissors and hard items for the frame are very helpful. Always combine two soft ingredients, then use scissors. Combine two hard ingredients, then use the frame. Critically, DO NOT combine a 'cut' item with a 'framed' item, as this consistently resulted in a ruined item with negative value in my experience. Your score is the value of the single most valuable item in your inventory, so once you have a high-value cut item (e.g., 80) and a framed item (e.g., 50), it is usually best to submit and secure the higher score, rather than attempting a final combination that might ruin everything.

Separately, combine two 'hard' ingredients (e.g., shell, buttons, rock, acorn, bark, wood), then use the 'frame' tool on that item for good scores (often 50). Do NOT combine more than two ingredients before using a tool. Do NOT mix soft and hard items or apply the wrong tool (scissors on hard, frame on soft) as this can lead to very low or negative values.
